We recommended that:
The Inventory Committee conduct a complete physical inventory of all PPE owned by the City Government and properly accomplish the Report of Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) indicating the complete details per inventoried item as to property description, property number, unit of measure, acquisition date and costs, balance per card, balance on hand and status/condition at the time of inspection;
The City Accountant record the 55 units of motor vehicles worth P52.550 million and provide adequate depreciation to reflect the fair value in the financial statements; and reclassify assets totaling P404.363 million to their appropriate accounts taking into consideration their respective accumulated depreciation;
The City Accountant and the City General Services Officer (CGSO) analyze the discrepancies noted in the balances of PPE accounts per physical count and SL/lapsing schedule to (i) effect the necessary adjustment in the books of accounts; (ii) prepare the Property Cards and PPE Ledger Cards for all items with complete details; and (iii) adjust the balances of accumulated depreciations for all PPE accounts to present fairly the PPE balances in the financial statements;
The Management create a Committee to conduct appraisal of all existing PPEs without cost to determine the fair value and the estimated remaining useful life for proper valuation of property in accordance with PPSAS 17; and
The concerned City officials facilitate the transfer of 15 land titles in the name of the City Government by providing sufficient funds for the transfer proceedings in order to acquire proof of ownership thereof.

We recommended that the City Accountant:
Analyze the discrepancies noted in the balances of PPE accounts and their corresponding accumulated depreciation in the SL and lapsing schedule to effect the necessary adjustments in the books of accounts;
Ensure that any changes in the accounting policy on the useful life and residual value in the computation of depreciation are promptly and completely adjusted in the books of accounts;
Ensure that the corresponding accumulated depreciation of PPE items are adjusted/transferred upon reclassification of assets to other PPE accounts;
Use consistently the percentage of residual value in all PPE items; and ensure that all PPE items are provided with depreciation until they are fully depreciated and/or derecognized; and
Identify PPE items acquired using the TCH-General Fund and prepare lapsing schedule for the provision of depreciation.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendations that:
Management advise all concerned offices to exert extensive efforts in retrieving the unrecorded disbursement vouchers and supporting documents covering the stale checks for immediate submission to the City Accounting Department to effect the necessary adjustment to related asset and government equity accounts;
The City Treasurer coordinate with the bank officials on the status of the requested copies of the bank’s debit and credit memos to support the necessary adjustment to related asset and government equity accounts;
The City  Treasurer  and  the  City  Accountant  conduct  quarterly reconciliation of the subsidiary ledger and  cashbook  balances  in compliance with Section 181 of the GAAM, Volume 1 to ensure the correctness and completeness of the recorded entries;
The City Treasurer, one month before the check become stale, notify the payee of the existence of the check; and
Management impose the appropriate actions  provided  under  Section 122 of Presidential Decree (PD) No.1445  against  liable  officials for the unjustified failure  to  submit  the  necessary  supporting documents.

We recommended that Management:

Strictly comply with the provision of COA Circular No. 92-382 dated July 3, 1992 which requires that only idle funds in the General Fund can be deposited under time deposit accounts upon prior authority of the Sanggunian and the approval of the local chief executive;
Stop the practice of investing Special Education Fund and Trust Fund under time deposit accounts as these funds have specific purposes and do not  fall  within   the  context  of   idle   fund   pursuant  to  COA Circular No. 93-382;
Unload the excessive investment in time deposits to expedite the settlement/remittance of amounts due to other government agencies and respective barangays including interests therefrom and to settle all financial obligations to creditors within due date;
Distribute proportionately the interests earned from the time deposits under the Trust  Fund  among  the  sources/fund  owners  in compliance with Section 311 of RA 7160; and
Adopt, by resolution, a comprehensive written investment  policy  to establish a set of basic procedures to meet investment objectives and to establish/maintain internal controls for accurate reporting and evaluation of investment results.

We recommended the following:
The General Services Officer/Inventory Committee prepare and submit the RPCI to support the  year-end  balance  of  Inventory  accounts totaling P249.376 million, pursuant to Section 124 of the NGAS Manual for LGU;
The concerned officials make sure that all  issuances  of  supplies  and materials are properly documented using the forms prescribed under applicable rules  and  regulations  on  supply  and  property management in local government units and comply with  Sections  121 and 123 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume I;
The City Engineer/GSO provide the  details/list  of  projects  that were implemented in 2017 to show how the construction materials and electrical supplies were utilized;
The concerned officials validate the existence of  the  inventories totaling P84,432,476.54 under the TCH-GF that  remained  non-moving for five years and make the necessary adjustments; and
The Management stop the practice of making  purchases  towards  the end of the year to avoid overstocking  of  supplies  and  materials that resulted to charging to CY 2017 appropriation of supplies  and materials that can be used only in the succeeding year.

We recommended that:
All concerned offices exert extensive efforts in retrieving the unrecorded/missing supporting documents for immediate submission to the City Accounting Department to effect the necessary adjustment to related asset and government equity accounts.
Henceforth, all concerned officials shall exercise the diligence of a good father of a family in safekeeping of public documents, recording and approving of transactions pursuant to Sections 122 and 127 of PD 1445. Failure to do so is subject to penal provisions under Article 218 of the Revised Penal Code;
The City Treasurer coordinate with the bank officials (i) on the status of the requested copies of the bank’s debit and credit memos to support the necessary adjustments; (ii) to request bank statements and to update records pertaining to LBP Account No. 1822-1029-52 Logo Find for BRS preparation; and (iii) to obtain copies of bank records covering the four closed account;
The City Treasurer and the City Accountant conduct quarterly reconciliation of the subsidiary ledgers for Cash in Bank-Local Currency, Current Account and Treasurer’s cashbook balances in compliance with Section 74 of PD1445 to ensure the correctness and completeness of the recorded entries;
The City Treasurer send a written notice to the payee of the existence of the check at least one month before a check becomes stale; and
Management impose appropriate actions provided under Sections 122 and 127 of PD 1445 against liable officials for the unjustified failure to submit the necessary supporting documents.

We recommended that:
The Inventory Committee conduct complete physical inventory of all PPEs owned by the City Government. To facilitate the inventory taking, the CGSO may require each office to conduct physical count of PPEs under their custody and prepare an inventory report that is complete in all particulars, such as, item description, model, serial number and property numbers, acquisition costs and dates, for submission to the Inventory Committee who in turn will validate the submitted inventory reports and come up with the consolidated RPCPPE;
The City Accountant and CGSO analyze the discrepancies noted in the balances of PPE accounts per physical count, subsidiary ledger and lapsing schedule to (i) effect the necessary adjustment in the books of accounts, (ii) prepare the Property Cards and PPE Ledger Cards with complete details, and (iii) adjust the balances of accumulated depreciations for all PPE accounts to present fairly the PPE balances in the financial statements;
The Management create a Committee to conduct appraisal of all existing PPEs without cost to determine the fair value and the estimated remaining useful life for proper valuation of property in accordance with PPSAS 17;
The City Accountant to effect necessary adjusting entries in the books of accounts to record misclassified assets under their appropriate accounts; and
The CGSO facilitate the transfer of 15 land titles in the name of the City Government and secure sufficient funds from the Office of the City Treasurer for the transfer proceedings in order to acquire proof of ownership thereof.

We recommended that:
The Inventory Committee prepare and submit the Report of Physical Count of Inventories, pursuant to Section 124 of the NGAS Manual for LGU;
The concerned officials make sure that all issuances of supplies or property are properly documented using the forms prescribed under applicable rules and regulations on supply and property management in local government units and comply with Sections 121 and 123 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume I;
The concerned officials validate the existence of the Inventories totaling P84.432 million under the TCH-GF that remained non-moving for four years and make the necessary adjustments;
The CGSO strictly comply with Section 7 of the Revised IRR of RA No.9184 and Section 373 of RA 7160 for a centralized and organized procurement of goods for various departments. The Local Chief Executive require all heads of offices to submit procurement plan of their supply requirements for the ensuing fiscal year to be incorporated in the APP prepared by the CGSO; and
The CGSO install and implement adequate controls on the custody and issuance of inventories of electrical/construction supplies and other supplies and materials to safeguard the assets of the City and to easily pinpoint accountability and responsibility for losses that may be incurred thereof.

We recommended that:
The Management strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 to ensure the proper granting, utilization and liquidation of all cash advances;
The City Treasurer and City Accountant compel all regular and special disbursing officers to liquidate their outstanding cash advances both for current and prior years. In case of failure to comply, we recommended for the withholding of their salaries without prejudice to the filing of appropriate charges against them as prescribed under CSC Resolution No. 040676 dated June 17, 2004;
The Management employs all possible means provided by law for the settlement or recovery of CAs granted to City officials and employees who are already separated from the government service;
The Accountant discontinue the granting of additional CA to officers who have unsettled CA and enforce liquidation of CA as soon as the prescribed periods for settlement becomes due; and
The Management develop monitoring system for CAs and issue demand letters to concerned officials and employees, requiring settlement of their outstanding cash advances.

We recommended that the Management:
Ensure the timely preparation of GAD Plan; the proper identification of PPAs in accordance with RA 10155; the implementation of PPAs within the target period; and closely monitor their progress so that the intended beneficiaries may avail of public services that will address the identified gender issues and concerns within the City;
Consider the option that payment to scholars of their benefits be made through ATM Card to minimize the grant of cash advances involving millions of pesos and to protect as well the safety of students-beneficiaries;
Ensure that no CAs will be granted in excess of each AO’s maximum cash accountability and to require the submission of the approved application for bond and/or Fidelity Bond as supporting document/s to DVs for the grant of CAs; and
Ensure that CAs are granted only to the personnel responsible for the implementation of PPAs for which the CAs are to be utilized.

We recommended that the City Solid Waste Management Board:
Adopt measures to promote and ensure the viability and effective implementation of solid waste management programs in its component barangays;
Monitor the implementation of the City Solid Waste Management Plan through its various political subdivisions and in cooperation with the private sector and the NGOs;
Review every two (2) years or as the need arises the City Solid Waste Management Plan for purposes of ensuring its sustainability, viability, effectiveness and relevance in relation to local and international developments in the field of solid waste management;
Develop the specific mechanics and guidelines for the implementation of the City Solid Waste Management Plan;
Recommend to the appropriate local government authorities specific measures or proposals for franchise or build-operate-transfer agreements with duly recognized institutions, pursuant to RA 6957, to provide either exclusive or non-exclusive authority for the collection, transfer, storage, processing, recycling or disposal of municipal solid waste. The proposals shall take into consideration appropriate government rules and regulations on contracts, franchise and build-operate-transfer agreements;
Recommend measures and safeguards against pollution and for the preservation of the natural ecosystem; and
Coordinate the efforts of its component barangays in the implementation of the City Solid Waste Management Plan.

We recommended that Management:
Require strict compliance on the submission of accounts and financial reports within the reporting deadlines in accordance with the aforementioned rules and regulations;
Direct the Department Heads concerned to submit all required financial accounts and reports within the deadlines – vouchers, payrolls, official receipts and its supporting documents as well as year-end Trial Balance, Balance Sheet, Statement of Income and Expenses and Statement of Cash Flows for each economic enterprises, to facilitate the examination and validation of Management’s assertions on the financial statements;
Direct the City Accountant to diligently perform his duties and responsibilities by reporting regularly to his office; keep monitoring and overseeing the progress of reviewing, recording and submission of transaction documents to the Office of the Auditor; and strengthen the internal control system of the City; and
Revisit/enhance the standard operating procedures in the preparation and processing of disbursement vouchers and payrolls to facilitate the prompt submission of said documents to the Office of the City Accountant. In such manner, the City Accountant may in turn submit the transaction documents to the Office of the Auditor within the period prescribed under Section 7.2.1(a) of COA Circular No. 2009-006 dated September 15, 2009.

We recommended that the CGSO:
Exercise control over the use of government vehicles through properly accomplished and duly approved and serially numbered Driver’s Trip Tickets, a summary of which shall be made at the end of the month in a Monthly Report of Official Travels for audit purposes;
Ensure that all vehicles owned by the city are bearing red plates except for security vehicles;
Submit the Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption to the Office of the City Auditor for verification purposes to determine reasonableness of fuel consumed; and
Ensure compliance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 77-61 dated September 26, 1977 for effective control of gasoline, oil and lubricants expenditures.
